<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18350202-647">
               <interp inst="t18350202-647" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18350202"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18350202-647" type="date" value="18350202"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18350202-647-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-647-18350202 t18350202-647-offence-1 t18350202-647-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18350202-647-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-647-18350202 t18350202-647-offence-1 t18350202-647-verdict-2"></join>
               <p>647. <persName id="def1-647-18350202" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-647-18350202" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-647-18350202" type="age" value="23"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-647-18350202" type="surname" value="PEACOCK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-647-18350202" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM PEACOCK</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-647-18350202" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-647-18350202" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-647-18350202" type="age" value="52"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-647-18350202" type="surname" value="FAIREY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-647-18350202" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS FAIREY</hi>
                  </persName> were indicted for<rs id="t18350202-647-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350202-647-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18350202-647-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> stealing, on the <rs id="t18350202-cd-147" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350202-647-offence-1 t18350202-cd-147"></join>20th of January</rs>, 4 1/2 lbs. of pork, value 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 3 1/2 lbs. of beef, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; and 1/2 lb. of suet, value 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18350202-name-1054" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1054" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1054" type="surname" value="PUTLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1054" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350202-647-offence-1 t18350202-name-1054"></join>George Putley</persName>, the master of the said <persName id="t18350202-name-1055" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1055" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1055" type="surname" value="PEACOCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1055" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350202-647-offence-1 t18350202-name-1055"></join>William Peacock</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350202-name-1056" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1056" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1056" type="surname" value="PUTLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1056" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE PUTLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in High-street, Borough. Peacock was in my employ for about three months as foreman—in consequence of information I received I spoke to Hack and Wilkinson, and the prisoners were appre<lb></lb>hended—Peacock was not authorized to sell on a Sunday—I do not open shop at all on a Sunday, at any time—if a regular customer sends, I may accommodate him, but then I expect to be applied to, before I allow him to serve—when I engaged him, he asked too much wages, and I said, "Remember, there is no Sunday work."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Has not he sometimes sold meat on a Sunday for you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not to my knowledge—I never received money from him on Monday, for meat sold on Sunday, nor of any other serrant—I did not tell him I never sold meat on Sunday except on an emergency—I did not authorize him to sell on a Sunday except to my own regular customers—I swear I did not tell him he might sell to my regular customers on Sunday—I never gave him permission to serve any customers on Sunday—it has happened somtimes that a customer may have sent for</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183502020179"></xptr>
               <p>a piece of meat, if they had been going out and altered their mind, rather than disoblige them, I have allowed them to have it—I do not recol<lb></lb>lect that that has happened in his time—I believe persons have come for a mutton chop or a neck of mutton during his time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did not you find on your desk 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., which he stated to you was payment for this meat? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There was 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on the desk on Sun<lb></lb>day morning, and he told me it was payment for the meat which had been taken—he told me this in the shop—he pointed out the money to me—when I came down stairs, after hearing the bell ring, the officer was in the shop—I had two other shopmen—neither of them were there—he told me immediately on being charged with having stolen this—the price of the meat found was about 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I believe Peacock's aunt has washed for him—there was some dirty linen found in the basket with the meat.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350202-name-1057" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1057" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1057" type="surname" value="WILKINSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1057" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WILKINSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am inspector of the police. In consequence of information, I watched the shop on Sunday, the 25th of January, I was on the opposite side of the street, from between six and seven o'clock till half-past eight o'clock—I saw the prisoner Fairey come opposite Mr. Putley's shop just before it struck eight by the church clock—he stood near the curb, looking towards the door, till half-past eight o'clock—he waited there half an hour—he neither rung nor knocked at the door—I observed Peacock open the door—he popped out, and took a hat-box, which Fairey had in his hand, and a basket—he turned into the shop, and was out again in a moment—he handed the basket to Fairey, who walked as fast as he could down towards London-bridge, till he came to Chapel-court—he turned up Chapel-court, and I apprehended him—I laid hold of the basket, and said, "It is all right"—I said to the constable behind me, "Take this man in charge"—I found a belly of pork very wet, as if it had just come from the pickling-tub, a piece of beef, and a piece of suet—I sent him to the station-house, and went directly to Mr. Putley's house—I rang the bell four times before it was answered, and then Peacock opened the door—I said, "We want you, I must see Mr. Putley directly"—he said he bad sold the meat—I had told him I wanted him for robbing his master—I said, "If you have sold it, what does it weigh?"—he said, "It weighed ten pounds"—that be had sold it at 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. per lb. and there was the money on the desk—there was half-a-crown, two shillings, and a sixpence on the desk—I looked at the scale, and it was quite dry and clean—the prosecutor came down directly, and I took Peacock into custody—at the watch-house, Fairey said the meat was paid for—I asked him how much—he said, it weighed seven pounds, and he had given half-a-crown for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was there not a cloth in the basket? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There was a butcher's woollen apron—he said at Union Hall next day, that he put the meat on the apron to be weighed, that it might not dirty the scale, but he did not say so at the station-house—I had not dirty the scale, of the meat to him, as weighing seven pounds—he said, "The meat"—Putley was in the shop all the time I was questioning Peacock, and must have heard all, I should think.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How were the articles placed in the basket—was the meat uppermost? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—the bundle of linen was on the top of the meat—then there was the pork, with the blue apron wrapped round it, and the beef and suet were under that, at the bottom of the basket—I saw the meat as soon as I laid hold of the basket, and pulled it open—it was a flag basket.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183502020180"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350202-name-1058" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1058" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1058" type="surname" value="ROSS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1058" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM ROSS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I was with Wilkinson, and took Fairey to the station-house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350202-name-1059" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1059" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1059" type="surname" value="NYE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1059" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM NYE</persName>
                  </hi>. I know Fairey by sight—I had seen him near the pro<lb></lb>secutor's shop several times at the door, the beginning of December last, and gave information to Mr. Putley.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Peacock's Defence.</hi> When the prisoner came to me on Sunday morn<lb></lb>ing, I gave him the basket, with my linen in it—he said he wanted some meat—I weighed this meat, and made it ten pounds—I put the apron and cloth into the scale—I gave him the meat—he gave me 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I said it was not enough—he said, "You owe me 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for washing, and whatever there is to pay, you must settle it"—I put the half crown on the desk, with 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. more, which the meat came to—I told him to go to the Blue Mead tap, and I would come to him, and pay him what I owed him for my washing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350202-name-1060" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1060" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1060" type="surname" value="WILKINSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1060" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WILKINSON</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined</hi>. The door was opened to me in about two minutes—Fairey had got the door of the Blue Mead tap in his hand, when I took hold of him—when I got into the prosecutor's house, the maid-servant was at the foot of the stain—I found a watch and some money in Peacock's box.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350202-name-1061" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1061" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1061" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-1061" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY WEBB</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the servant. I heard the bell ring—the prisoner was in the kitchen when it rang, and went down to answer it, but he did not go till it rang three times—he went down the first time it rang—it rang three times more, and then I went down, as he did not open it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Do you know Fairey was in the habit of coming for the dirty linen? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The bell never rang in the morning, and I never saw any body come for his dirty linen.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Fairey's Defence.</hi> I went to the shop for his linen—sometimes I ring at the bell, and sometimes I do not ring—when he came out, I have said to him, "If you have a bit of meat to suit me, put it in, that will do instead of the washing"—I said that morning, "Seven or eight pounds will do for me this morning"—he put this in—I gave him 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he said it was not enough—I said, "You pay the difference, and I will settle it when you come to me"—I was going into the public-house door, when the sergeant of the police caught hold of me, and said, "I have been looking for you a good while, I want what you have in that basket"—I said, "What I have is my own, I have paid for it"—he said to the policeman, "You take him, I will go after the other"—at the station-house, he asked how much the meat came to, and I said, I gave half-a-crown for it.</p>
               <p>(Moses Woolf, of Rosemary-lane; John Glanville, painter and glazier, Hackney-road; and Ann Noakes, Green Gate-gardens, Hackney-road, deposed to the prisoner Fairey's good character; and Charles Cook, butcher, Red Lion-street, Holborn; and Andrew Curry, boot-maker, Phoenix-street, to that of Peacock.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">PEACOCK</hi>. <rs id="t18350202-647-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350202-647-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18350202-647-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GUILTY</hi>
                  </rs>.—Aged 23.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">FAIREY.</hi> 
                  <rs id="t18350202-647-verdict-2" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350202-647-verdict-2" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18350202-647-verdict-2" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GUILTY</hi>
                  </rs>.—Aged 52.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Recommended to mercy on account of their previous good character</hi>.—<rs id="t18350202-647-punishment-134" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350202-647-punishment-134" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
